[Tom Wheeler] There's a really simple issue

00:09:13.730 --> 00:09:24.830
that I think that we're going to have to face
again because of the new administration, and

00:09:24.830 --> 00:09:33.860
that is that privacy is a civil rights issue
of the 21st century, of the connected era.

00:09:33.860 --> 00:09:48.500
Let me give you an example of it. We had,
for decades, rules that applied to telephone

00:09:48.500 --> 00:10:00.500
companies that said that the information that
was transmitted in order to set up the call

00:10:00.500 --> 00:10:08.750
could not be used by the telephone companies.
For instance, if I call Air France, Verizon

00:10:08.750 --> 00:10:13.050
can't turn around and sell that information
to some tour operator or hotel company in

00:10:13.050 --> 00:10:19.620
Paris.
That doesn't exist in the broadband world.

00:10:19.620 --> 00:10:26.780
You had that strange situation where your
smartphone, if you used it to make a voice

00:10:26.780 --> 00:10:33.040
call, your privacy was protected. If you use
that same device and the same network to go

00:10:33.040 --> 00:10:39.370
on the web and go to the Air France website,
that information was for sale. It was not

00:10:39.370 --> 00:10:45.250
your information anymore. The very fact that
you had used the network meant you were giving

00:10:45.250 --> 00:10:52.390
that information. We said no. This is the
consumers' information, and so we put a rule

00:10:52.390 --> 00:10:58.960
in place that said that the consumer gets
to make the choice as to how the network is

00:10:58.960 --> 00:11:04.589
going to use the information. That was another
one of our three to two votes.

